%tensorflow_version 1.x
import tensorflow as tf
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import helper as hlp


# Distance function for K-means (squared pairwise distance for all pairs of N datapoints and K clusters)
def distanceFunc(X, MU):
    # Inputs
    # X: is an NxD matrix (N observations and D dimensions)
    # MU: is an KxD matrix (K means and D dimensions)
    # Outputs
    # pair_dist: is the squared pairwise distance matrix (NxK)

    X = tf.expand_dims(X, 1)        # shape NxD -> Nx1xD
    MU = tf.expand_dims(MU, 0)      # shape KxD -> 1xKxD
    distance = tf.subtract(X, MU)   # shape NxKxD
    distance = tf.square(distance)  
    distance = tf.reduce_sum(distance, 2) # reduce the sum along the third dimension, -> NxK

    return distance


# define the K-mean graph
def buildGraph(learning_rate, beta1, beta2, epsilon, K, D):

    # a. initilize center of the cluster
    MU = tf.Variable(tf.random_normal([K,D], mean=0, stddev=1)) # shape KxD, initilized by standard normal distribution

    # b. placeholders for data
    X = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, name='X') # shape NxD

    # c. calculate the loss tensor based on the function
    distance = distanceFunc(X, MU)
    distance_min = tf.reduce_min(distance, 1) # find min and reduce along the second dimension ->N
    loss = tf.reduce_sum(distance_min)

    # d. Compute the Adam optimizer with assigned hyperparameters
    optimizer = tf.train.AdamOptimizer(learning_rate, beta1, beta2, epsilon).minimize(loss) 

    # e. compute for clustering  
    MU_new = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, name= 'MU_new')
    cluster = tf.argmin(distanceFunc(X, MU_new), 1) # NxK -> find the index of minimum value within each row, A Tensor of type output_type.

    return MU, X, loss, optimizer, MU_new, cluster


# define the K-mean function
def kmeans(K, is_valid, num):  
    # input: K - number of clusters, is_valid - for validation set, num - data2D/data100D selection

    # Loading data
    if num==2:
        data = np.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/data2D.npy')
    elif num==100:
        data = np.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/data100D.npy')
    [num_pts, dim] = np.shape(data)

    # For Validation set
    if is_valid:
        valid_batch = int(num_pts / 3.0)
        np.random.seed(45689)
        rnd_idx = np.arange(num_pts)
        np.random.shuffle(rnd_idx)
        val_data = data[rnd_idx[:valid_batch]]
        data = data[rnd_idx[valid_batch:]]

    # parameter declarations
    N = num_pts
    D = dim

    learning_rate = 0.1
    beta1 = 0.9
    beta2 = 0.99
    epsilon = 1e-5
    updates = 1000        # the learning should converge within a few hudred updates

    # include a plot of the loss vs the number of updates
    train_loss = np.zeros(updates)
    val_loss = np.zeros(updates)

    MU, X, loss, optimizer, MU_new, cluster = buildGraph(learning_rate, beta1, beta2, epsilon, K, D)

    init = tf.global_variables_initializer()
    with tf.Session() as sess:
        sess.run(init)

        for i in range(updates):    
            
            # compute the optimizer, and store the training loss
            mu, train_loss_i, _ = sess.run([MU, loss, optimizer], feed_dict={X:data})
            train_loss[i] = train_loss_i

            if is_valid:
                # compute and store the validation loss
                mu_val, val_loss_i = sess.run([MU, loss], {X:val_data})
                val_loss[i] = val_loss_i
            
                # print info every 20 iteration or is the last update
                if i%20==0 or i==updates-1:
                    print("Iteration num = " + str(i+1) + " / training loss = " + str(train_loss_i) + " / validation loss = " + str(val_loss_i))

            else:
                # print info every 20 iteration or is the last update
                if i%20==0 or i==updates-1:
                    print("Iteration num = " + str(i+1) + " / training loss = " + str(train_loss_i))

            # computer the new clustering with the updated mu
            clustering = sess.run([cluster], {X:data, MU_new:mu}) 

    # run K-means on data100D.npy, compare the validation loss (no need for graph)
    if num == 100:
        clustering = clustering[0] # -> 1xN
        for i in range(K):
            # percentage of each cluster
            percentage = np.sum(np.equal(i, clustering)) / len(clustering) * 100
            print("cluster " + str(i+1) + ": " + str(percentage))
        return val_loss

    # include a plot of the loss vs the number of updates
    plt.title('Training / (Validation) loss ')
    plt.plot(range(1,updates+1), train_loss, label="Trainning")
    if is_valid == True:
        plt.plot(range(1,updates+1), val_loss, label="Validation")
    plt.xlabel("number of updates")
    plt.ylabel("loss")
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.show()

    print('Training Loss:', train_loss[-1])
    if is_valid == True:
        print('Validation Loss:', val_loss[-1])   

    # include a 2D scatter plot of training data points colored by their cluster assignments
    clustering = clustering[0]  # -> 1xN
    for i in range(K):
        # percentage of each cluster
        percentage = np.sum(np.equal(i, clustering)) / len(clustering) * 100
        
        cluster_i = []
        for j in range(len(clustering)):
            # each training data's closest cluster it belongs to == the current cluster
            if clustering[j] == i:    
                cluster_i.append(data[j,:])
        cluster_i = np.array(cluster_i)
        
        # plt.scatter(data position x, data position y, marker size s, with label)
        plt.scatter(cluster_i[:,0], cluster_i[:,1], s = 5, label = 'cluster '+str(i+1)+': '+str(round(percentage,3))+'%')
   
    plt.title('2D scatter plot when K = ' + str(K))
    plt.scatter(mu[:,0], mu[:,1], marker = '*', c='black')

    if is_valid == True:
        plt.xlabel('x1 \n\n validation loss is '+ str(val_loss[-1]) + ' when K = ' + str(K))
    else:
       plt.xlabel('x1 \n\n validation loss is not asked to compute' + ' when K = ' + str(K))
    plt.ylabel('x2')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.show()

    # for final comparison according to validation loss
    if is_valid == True: 
        return val_loss[-1]    
  

if __name__ == '__main__':

    print("----------------------------------------------------------------data2D.npy\n")
    
    kmeans(3, False, 2)
    val_loss = []
    val_loss.append(kmeans(1, True, 2))
    val_loss.append(kmeans(2, True, 2))
    val_loss.append(kmeans(3, True, 2))
    val_loss.append(kmeans(4, True, 2))
    val_loss.append(kmeans(5, True, 2))

    plt.title('Validation loss')
    plt.plot(range(1, 5+1), val_loss)
    plt.xlabel('number of clusters - K')
    plt.ylabel('loss')
    plt.show()

    print("\n\n----------------------------------------------------------------data100D.npy\n")
    
    val_loss = []
    K = [5, 10, 15, 20, 30]
    for i in range(len(K)):
        val_loss.append(kmeans(K[i], True, 100))  # hold out 1/3 of the data for validation
        plt.plot(range(1, 1000+1), val_loss[-1], label="K = " + str(K[i]))

    plt.title('Validation loss for K-means')
    plt.xlabel('number of updates')
    plt.ylabel('loss')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.show()

import tensorflow as tf
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
#import helper as hlp


# helper function copied from helper.py file
def reduce_logsumexp(input_tensor, reduction_indices=1, keep_dims=False):
  """Computes the sum of elements across dimensions of a tensor in log domain.

     It uses a similar API to tf.reduce_sum.

  Args:
    input_tensor: The tensor to reduce. Should have numeric type.
    reduction_indices: The dimensions to reduce. 
    keep_dims: If true, retains reduced dimensions with length 1.
  Returns:
    The reduced tensor.
  """
  max_input_tensor1 = tf.reduce_max(
      input_tensor, reduction_indices, keep_dims=keep_dims)
  max_input_tensor2 = max_input_tensor1
  if not keep_dims:
    max_input_tensor2 = tf.expand_dims(max_input_tensor2, reduction_indices)
  return tf.log(
      tf.reduce_sum(
          tf.exp(input_tensor - max_input_tensor2),
          reduction_indices,
          keep_dims=keep_dims)) + max_input_tensor1


# helper function copied from helper.py file
def logsoftmax(input_tensor):
  """Computes normal softmax nonlinearity in log domain.

     It can be used to normalize log probability.
     The softmax is always computed along the second dimension of the input Tensor.     

  Args:
    input_tensor: Unnormalized log probability.
  Returns:
    normalized log probability.
  """
  return input_tensor - reduce_logsumexp(input_tensor, reduction_indices=0, keep_dims=True)


# Distance function for GMM
def distanceFunc(X, MU):
    # Inputs
    # X: is an NxD matrix (N observations and D dimensions)
    # MU: is an KxD matrix (K means and D dimensions)
    # Outputs
    # pair_dist: is the pairwise distance matrix (NxK)
    
    X = tf.expand_dims(X, 1)        # shape NxD -> Nx1xD
    MU = tf.expand_dims(MU, 0)      # shape KxD -> 1xKxD
    distance = tf.subtract(X, MU)   # shape NxKxD
    distance = tf.square(distance)  
    distance = tf.reduce_sum(distance, 2) # reduce the sum along the third dimension, -> NxK

    return distance


# computing the log probability density function for cluster k: logN(x; mu^k, sigma^k^2) 
# for all pair of N data points and K clusters
def log_GaussPDF(X, mu, sigma):
    # Inputs
    # X: N X D
    # mu: K X D
    # sigma: K X 1
 
    # Outputs
    # log Gaussian PDF N X K

    d = X.shape[1].value  # d = D
    sigma = tf.squeeze(sigma) # Kx1 -> K
    log = -1*(d/2)*tf.log(2*np.pi*tf.square(sigma))

    distance = distanceFunc(X, mu)
    exp = (-1*distance)/(2*tf.square(sigma))

    return log + exp


# computing the log probability of the cluster variable z given the data vector x: logP(z|x)
def log_posterior(log_PDF, log_pi):
    # Input
    # log_PDF: log Gaussian PDF N X K
    # log_pi: K X 1

    # Outputs
    # log_post: N X K

    log_pi = tf.squeeze(log_pi) # Kx1 -> K
    log_post = log_PDF + log_pi - reduce_logsumexp(log_PDF + log_pi, keep_dims=True)
    return log_post


# define the GMM graph
def buildGraph(learning_rate, beta1, beta2, epsilon, K, D):

    # a. initilize center of the cluster
    MU = tf.Variable(tf.random_normal([K,D], mean=0, stddev=1)) # shape KxD, initilized by standard normal distribution
    phi = tf.Variable(tf.random_normal([K,1], mean=0, stddev=1)) # shape Kx1, initilized by standard normal distribution
    psi = tf.Variable(tf.random_normal([K,1], mean=0, stddev=1)) # shape Kx1, initilized by standard normal distribution

    # b. placeholders for data
    X = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, [None, D], name='X') # shape NxD

    # c. calculate the loss tensor based on the function
    sigma = tf.sqrt(tf.exp(phi))
    log_PDF = log_GaussPDF(X, MU, sigma)
    log_pi = logsoftmax(psi)
    loss = -1*tf.reduce_sum(reduce_logsumexp(log_PDF + tf.squeeze(log_pi), keep_dims=True))

    # d. Compute the Adam optimizer with assigned hyperparameters
    optimizer = tf.train.AdamOptimizer(learning_rate, beta1, beta2, epsilon).minimize(loss) 

    # e. compute for clustering  
    cluster = tf.argmax(log_posterior(log_PDF, log_pi), 1) # Returns index_arrayndarray of ints

    return MU, phi, psi, X, sigma, log_PDF, log_pi, loss, optimizer, cluster


# define the GMM function
def GMM(K, is_valid, num):
    # input: K - number of clusters, is_valid - for validation set, num - data2D/data100D selection

    # Loading data
    if num==2:
        data = np.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/data2D.npy')
    elif num==100:
        data = np.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/data100D.npy')
    [num_pts, dim] = np.shape(data)

    # For Validation set
    if is_valid:
        valid_batch = int(num_pts / 3.0)
        np.random.seed(45689)
        rnd_idx = np.arange(num_pts)
        np.random.shuffle(rnd_idx)
        val_data = data[rnd_idx[:valid_batch]]
        data = data[rnd_idx[valid_batch:]]

    # parameter declarations
    N = num_pts
    D = dim

    learning_rate = 0.1
    beta1 = 0.9
    beta2 = 0.99
    epsilon = 1e-5
    updates = 1000        # the learning should converge within a few hudred updates

    # include a plot of the loss vs the number of updates
    train_loss = np.zeros(updates)
    val_loss = np.zeros(updates)

    MU, phi, psi, X, sigma, log_PDF, log_pi, loss, optimizer, cluster = buildGraph(learning_rate, beta1, beta2, epsilon, K, D)

    init = tf.global_variables_initializer()
    with tf.Session() as sess:
        sess.run(init)

        for i in range(updates):      
            
            # compute the optimizer, and store the training loss, find the clustering value
            mu, SIGMA, _, LOG_PI, train_loss_i, _, clustering = sess.run([MU, sigma, log_PDF, log_pi, loss, optimizer, cluster], feed_dict={X:data})
            train_loss[i] = train_loss_i

            if is_valid:
                # compute and store the validation loss
                _, val_loss_i = sess.run([MU, loss], {X:val_data})
                val_loss[i] = val_loss_i
            
                # print info every 20 iteration or is the last update
                if i%20==0 or i==updates-1:
                    print("Iteration num = " + str(i+1) + " / training loss = " + str(train_loss_i) + " / validation loss = " + str(val_loss_i))

            else:
                # print info every 20 iteration or is the last update
                if i%20==0 or i==updates-1:
                    print("Iteration num = " + str(i+1) + " / training loss = " + str(train_loss_i))

    # run GMM on data100D.npy, compare the validation loss (no need for graph)
    if num == 100:
        for i in range(K):
            # percentage of each cluster
            percentage = np.sum(np.equal(i, clustering)) / len(clustering) * 100
            print("cluster " + str(i+1) + ": " + str(percentage))
        return val_loss

    # print out some parameters
    print('\n mu:')
    print(mu)
    print('sigma:')
    print(SIGMA)
    print('pi:')
    print(np.exp(LOG_PI))


    # include a plot of the loss vs the number of updates
    plt.title('Training / (Validation) loss ')
    plt.plot(range(1,updates+1), train_loss, label="Trainning")
    if is_valid == True:
        plt.plot(range(1,updates+1), val_loss, label="Validation")
    plt.xlabel("number of updates")
    plt.ylabel("loss")
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.show()

    print('Training Loss:', train_loss[-1])
    if is_valid == True:
        print('Validation Loss:', val_loss[-1])   

    # include a 2D scatter plot of training data points colored by their cluster assignments
    for i in range(K):
        # percentage of each cluster
        percentage = np.sum(np.equal(i, clustering)) / len(clustering) * 100
        
        cluster_i = []
        for j in range(len(clustering)):
            # each training data's closest cluster it belongs to == the current cluster
            if clustering[j] == i:    
                cluster_i.append(data[j,:])
        cluster_i = np.array(cluster_i)
        
        if cluster_i.shape[0] != 0:
            # plt.scatter(data position x, data position y, marker size s, with label)
            plt.scatter(cluster_i[:,0], cluster_i[:,1], s = 5, label = 'cluster '+str(i+1)+': '+str(round(percentage,3))+'%')
   
    plt.title('2D scatter plot when K = ' + str(K))
    plt.scatter(mu[:,0], mu[:,1], marker = '*', c='black')

    if is_valid == True:
        plt.xlabel('x1 \n\n validation loss is '+ str(val_loss[-1]) + ' when K = ' + str(K))
    else:
       plt.xlabel('x1 \n\n validation loss is not asked to compute' + ' when K = ' + str(K))
    plt.ylabel('x2')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.show()

    # for final comparison according to validation loss
    if is_valid == True: 
        return val_loss[-1]

%tensorflow_version 1.x
import tensorflow as tf
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
#import helper as hlp


# helper function copied from helper.py file
def reduce_logsumexp(input_tensor, reduction_indices=1, keep_dims=False):
  """Computes the sum of elements across dimensions of a tensor in log domain.

     It uses a similar API to tf.reduce_sum.

  Args:
    input_tensor: The tensor to reduce. Should have numeric type.
    reduction_indices: The dimensions to reduce. 
    keep_dims: If true, retains reduced dimensions with length 1.
  Returns:
    The reduced tensor.
  """
  max_input_tensor1 = tf.reduce_max(
      input_tensor, reduction_indices, keep_dims=keep_dims)
  max_input_tensor2 = max_input_tensor1
  if not keep_dims:
    max_input_tensor2 = tf.expand_dims(max_input_tensor2, reduction_indices)
  return tf.log(
      tf.reduce_sum(
          tf.exp(input_tensor - max_input_tensor2),
          reduction_indices,
          keep_dims=keep_dims)) + max_input_tensor1


# helper function copied from helper.py file
def logsoftmax(input_tensor):
  """Computes normal softmax nonlinearity in log domain.

     It can be used to normalize log probability.
     The softmax is always computed along the second dimension of the input Tensor.     

  Args:
    input_tensor: Unnormalized log probability.
  Returns:
    normalized log probability.
  """
  return input_tensor - reduce_logsumexp(input_tensor, reduction_indices=0, keep_dims=True)


# Distance function for GMM
def distanceFunc(X, MU):
    # Inputs
    # X: is an NxD matrix (N observations and D dimensions)
    # MU: is an KxD matrix (K means and D dimensions)
    # Outputs
    # pair_dist: is the pairwise distance matrix (NxK)
    
    X = tf.expand_dims(X, 1)        # shape NxD -> Nx1xD
    MU = tf.expand_dims(MU, 0)      # shape KxD -> 1xKxD
    distance = tf.subtract(X, MU)   # shape NxKxD
    distance = tf.square(distance)  
    distance = tf.reduce_sum(distance, 2) # reduce the sum along the third dimension, -> NxK

    return distance


# computing the log probability density function for cluster k: logN(x; mu^k, sigma^k^2) 
# for all pair of N data points and K clusters
def log_GaussPDF(X, mu, sigma):
    # Inputs
    # X: N X D
    # mu: K X D
    # sigma: K X 1
 
    # Outputs
    # log Gaussian PDF N X K

    d = X.shape[1].value  # d = D
    sigma = tf.squeeze(sigma) # Kx1 -> K
    log = -1*(d/2)*tf.log(2*np.pi*tf.square(sigma))

    distance = distanceFunc(X, mu)
    exp = (-1*distance)/(2*tf.square(sigma))

    return log + exp


# computing the log probability of the cluster variable z given the data vector x: logP(z|x)
def log_posterior(log_PDF, log_pi):
    # Input
    # log_PDF: log Gaussian PDF N X K
    # log_pi: K X 1

    # Outputs
    # log_post: N X K

    log_pi = tf.squeeze(log_pi) # Kx1 -> K
    log_post = log_PDF + log_pi - reduce_logsumexp(log_PDF + log_pi, keep_dims=True)
    return log_post


# define the GMM graph
def buildGraph(learning_rate, beta1, beta2, epsilon, K, D):

    # a. initilize center of the cluster
    MU = tf.Variable(tf.random_normal([K,D], mean=0, stddev=1)) # shape KxD, initilized by standard normal distribution
    phi = tf.Variable(tf.random_normal([K,1], mean=0, stddev=1)) # shape Kx1, initilized by standard normal distribution
    psi = tf.Variable(tf.random_normal([K,1], mean=0, stddev=1)) # shape Kx1, initilized by standard normal distribution

    # b. placeholders for data
    X = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, [None, D], name='X') # shape NxD

    # c. calculate the loss tensor based on the function
    sigma = tf.sqrt(tf.exp(phi))
    log_PDF = log_GaussPDF(X, MU, sigma)
    log_pi = logsoftmax(psi)
    loss = -1*tf.reduce_sum(reduce_logsumexp(log_PDF + tf.squeeze(log_pi), keep_dims=True))

    # d. Compute the Adam optimizer with assigned hyperparameters
    optimizer = tf.train.AdamOptimizer(learning_rate, beta1, beta2, epsilon).minimize(loss) 

    # e. compute for clustering  
    cluster = tf.argmax(log_posterior(log_PDF, log_pi), 1) # Returns index_arrayndarray of ints

    return MU, phi, psi, X, sigma, log_PDF, log_pi, loss, optimizer, cluster


# define the GMM function
def GMM(K, is_valid, num):
    # input: K - number of clusters, is_valid - for validation set, num - data2D/data100D selection

    # Loading data
    if num==2:
        data = np.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/data2D.npy')
    elif num==100:
        data = np.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/data100D.npy')
    [num_pts, dim] = np.shape(data)

    # For Validation set
    if is_valid:
        valid_batch = int(num_pts / 3.0)
        np.random.seed(45689)
        rnd_idx = np.arange(num_pts)
        np.random.shuffle(rnd_idx)
        val_data = data[rnd_idx[:valid_batch]]
        data = data[rnd_idx[valid_batch:]]

    # parameter declarations
    N = num_pts
    D = dim

    learning_rate = 0.1
    beta1 = 0.9
    beta2 = 0.99
    epsilon = 1e-5
    updates = 1000        # the learning should converge within a few hudred updates

    # include a plot of the loss vs the number of updates
    train_loss = np.zeros(updates)
    val_loss = np.zeros(updates)

    MU, phi, psi, X, sigma, log_PDF, log_pi, loss, optimizer, cluster = buildGraph(learning_rate, beta1, beta2, epsilon, K, D)

    init = tf.global_variables_initializer()
    with tf.Session() as sess:
        sess.run(init)

        for i in range(updates):      
            
            # compute the optimizer, and store the training loss, find the clustering value
            mu, SIGMA, _, LOG_PI, train_loss_i, _, clustering = sess.run([MU, sigma, log_PDF, log_pi, loss, optimizer, cluster], feed_dict={X:data})
            train_loss[i] = train_loss_i

            if is_valid:
                # compute and store the validation loss
                _, val_loss_i = sess.run([MU, loss], {X:val_data})
                val_loss[i] = val_loss_i
            
                # print info every 20 iteration or is the last update
                if i%20==0 or i==updates-1:
                    print("Iteration num = " + str(i+1) + " / training loss = " + str(train_loss_i) + " / validation loss = " + str(val_loss_i))

            else:
                # print info every 20 iteration or is the last update
                if i%20==0 or i==updates-1:
                    print("Iteration num = " + str(i+1) + " / training loss = " + str(train_loss_i))

    # run GMM on data100D.npy, compare the validation loss (no need for graph)
    if num == 100:
        for i in range(K):
            # percentage of each cluster
            percentage = np.sum(np.equal(i, clustering)) / len(clustering) * 100
            print("cluster " + str(i+1) + ": " + str(percentage))
        return val_loss

    # print out some parameters
    print('\n mu:')
    print(mu)
    print('sigma:')
    print(SIGMA)
    print('pi:')
    print(np.exp(LOG_PI))


    # include a plot of the loss vs the number of updates
    plt.title('Training / (Validation) loss ')
    plt.plot(range(1,updates+1), train_loss, label="Trainning")
    if is_valid == True:
        plt.plot(range(1,updates+1), val_loss, label="Validation")
    plt.xlabel("number of updates")
    plt.ylabel("loss")
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.show()

    print('Training Loss:', train_loss[-1])
    if is_valid == True:
        print('Validation Loss:', val_loss[-1])   

    # include a 2D scatter plot of training data points colored by their cluster assignments
    for i in range(K):
        # percentage of each cluster
        percentage = np.sum(np.equal(i, clustering)) / len(clustering) * 100
        
        cluster_i = []
        for j in range(len(clustering)):
            # each training data's closest cluster it belongs to == the current cluster
            if clustering[j] == i:    
                cluster_i.append(data[j,:])
        cluster_i = np.array(cluster_i)
        
        if cluster_i.shape[0] != 0:
            # plt.scatter(data position x, data position y, marker size s, with label)
            plt.scatter(cluster_i[:,0], cluster_i[:,1], s = 5, label = 'cluster '+str(i+1)+': '+str(round(percentage,3))+'%')
   
    plt.title('2D scatter plot when K = ' + str(K))
    plt.scatter(mu[:,0], mu[:,1], marker = '*', c='black')

    if is_valid == True:
        plt.xlabel('x1 \n\n validation loss is '+ str(val_loss[-1]) + ' when K = ' + str(K))
    else:
       plt.xlabel('x1 \n\n validation loss is not asked to compute' + ' when K = ' + str(K))
    plt.ylabel('x2')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.show()

    # for final comparison according to validation loss
    if is_valid == True: 
        return val_loss[-1]    
  
if __name__ == '__main__':
